      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software used in the analysis is under version control, with documented test suite and release notes for the solver version employed.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical is a commercially validated FEA solver subject to ISO 9001-compliant QA processes. Release notes and verification test suite results for the 2026-Q1 build series are on file. Internal DePuy Synthes QA records confirm the solver installation was qualified on the analysis workstation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations for structural mechanics with contact.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical passes NAFEMS benchmark suite for linear and nonlinear structural problems. Contact patch test results for frictional contact elements are documented in the solver verification report. No anomalies identified for the element types and contact formulations used in this model."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change <2% between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation applied to estimate discretization uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry (coarse ~0.6 M, medium ~1.2 M, fine ~2.4 M elements). Stiffness QoI changed by 1.4% between medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation yields a discretization uncertainty of ±1.1% for stiffness and ±1.7% for yield force, both within the 2% acceptance threshold. The medium mesh (~1.2 M elements) was selected for the validation study."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual norms and energy balance monitored; convergence criteria documented and shown to be sufficient for QoI accuracy.",
      "rationale": "Force residual convergence criterion set to 1×10⁻⁴ (relative). Energy residual monitored at each load step; maximum energy imbalance across all simulations was 0.08%. Iterative contact stabilization convergence confirmed by zero-penetration check at final load step. No non-converged load steps were accepted."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup reviewed by an independent analyst; boundary conditions, loading, and material assignments verified against the ASTM F1717 protocol and device specifications.",
      "rationale": "An independent FEA analyst (not the model developer) performed a documented review of boundary conditions, material property assignments, contact pair definitions, and loading protocol against the ASTM F1717 standard and the device design specification. Three minor discrepancies were identified and corrected prior to the validation runs. Final model setup sign-off is on file."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum mechanics with large-deformation elastoplasticity and frictional contact is an appropriate model form for metallic pedicle screw constructs under quasi-static bending; justification documented.",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw construct is a metallic assembly (Ti-6Al-4V screw, cobalt-chrome rod) subject to quasi-static displacement-controlled bending. Continuum elastoplastic FEA with frictional contact is the standard model form for this class of problem and is consistent with FDA guidance on computational modeling of orthopedic implants. Viscoelastic and dynamic effects are negligible at the prescribed loading rate (5 mm/min)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties, geometric dimensions, and contact parameters are traceable to material certifications and dimensional inspection reports; sensitivity analysis performed for uncertain inputs.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties (E=113.8 GPa, σ_y=880 MPa, tangent modulus from tensile coupon testing) are traceable to lot-specific material certifications. CoCr rod properties from supplier datasheet, confirmed by in-house tensile testing. Geometric model derived from CAD nominal with dimensional inspection confirming as-built dimensions within ±0.05 mm. Sensitivity analysis showed friction coefficient (μ=0.15–0.25) produced <3% variation in stiffness QoI."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from production-representative lots; dimensional inspection confirms geometric conformance; traceability to device history records established.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production-representative components (same lot series as commercial product). Dimensional inspection of screw outer diameter, thread pitch, and tulip geometry confirmed conformance to nominal within drawing tolerances. Traceability to device history records and material certifications documented for all 11 constructs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of COU loading scenarios; at minimum two independent test configurations or loading rates evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single ASTM F1717 configuration (compression-bending, 5 mm/min, room temperature, dry). While this is the standard regulatory test condition, only one loading condition was evaluated. Tension-bending and fatigue conditions were not included in this validation activity. This factor is intentionally below the required level; the gap is acknowledged and accepted given the regulatory precedent for the single-condition approach."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions) are demonstrably equivalent to the test article and test setup; any deviations are quantified and their impact assessed.",
      "rationale": "FEA geometry was derived from the same CAD nominal used to manufacture the test constructs. Material properties were measured from coupons from the same material lots. Boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry (upper and lower grips modeled as rigid bodies with measured grip separation of 44 mm). The only deliberate simplification was omission of the polyaxial tulip spring mechanism, which was shown by sensitivity analysis to contribute <1% to construct stiffness."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of FEA predictions to experimental measurements using pre-specified acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval <1.96); statistical summary reported.",
      "rationale": "FEA predictions vs. experimental means (N=11): stiffness 187 N/mm vs. 192±8 N/mm (2.6% difference, E/uval=0.62); yield force 412 N vs. 421±19 N (2.1% difference, E/uval=0.47); force at 40 mm displacement 683 N vs. 701±24 N (2.6% difference, E/uval=0.75). All three QoIs satisfy both pre-specified acceptance bounds. Results are consistent across both laboratories (inter-lab CV <4%)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected for validation (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly relevant to the clinical failure modes and the regulatory submission claims.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing between implant and bone graft; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement are the primary regulatory endpoints per ASTM F1717 and FDA 510(k) guidance for spinal pedicle screw systems. These QoIs are directly linked to the clinical risk of implant fatigue fracture and are the quantities cited in the predicate device comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario (ASTM F1717 compression-bending, non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw) is representative of the intended COU; any interpolation or extrapolation beyond the validated domain is bounded.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: same device geometry (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw), same loading protocol (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending), same material system, and same assembly configuration. No extrapolation beyond the validated domain is required for the regulatory submission claim. The FEA model will not be applied to cannulated variants or dynamic loading without separate validation."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 factors. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed the required credibility level. The single below-requirement factor (Test conditions, achieved 2 vs. required 3) is accepted on the basis of regulatory precedent for the ASTM F1717 single-condition approach and is consistent with the predicate device submission strategy. The FEA model ensemble is judged credible for supporting the regulatory claim. Note: the validation results were generated under ModelConfiguration ansys-mechanical-2026-q1-build-7-rc2, which is the release candidate immediately preceding the current production build ansys-mechanical-2026-q1-build-7. The team assessed this configuration as effectively the same build, as the sole patch between rc2 and the release addressed a contact stabilization coefficient adjustment not expected to affect quasi-static structural predictions. The validation suite was not re-executed under the released build prior to this submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
